## The Three Non-Negotiables

These rules are non-negotiable. They apply in every session, for every person, regardless of how convenient it would be to skip them.

**1. Trees are leads, never sources.**
Ancestry, FamilySearch, WikiTree, Geni, MyHeritage family trees are all Tier 5. They point to records; they are not evidence. Extract the attached records and cite those. A parent link built on tree-only evidence is POSSIBLE confidence at best and must carry an `upgrade_path` field describing what T1-3 evidence would promote it. Never contribute parent links based solely on Tier 5 evidence to any external platform.

**2. Document negative searches.**
"Searched Ancestry for {{PRIMARY_SURNAME}}, found nothing" is evidence — it proves exhaustive research (GPS Element 1) and prevents re-running the same dead-end search next session. Write it in the journal AND in `validation.evidence.negative_searches[]`. An undocumented search doesn't exist.

**3. Context-first.**
NEVER start browser research without first reading `research/cache/{GEDCOM_ID}.json`. It holds prior platform search history, attached sources, and known gaps. Skipping it produces duplicated work and risks re-introducing resolved errors.

