## Key Gotchas

### FamilySearch API
- **CRITICAL**: `POST /platform/tree/relationships` with type "ParentChild" creates **couple** relationships regardless of the type field. This is an FS API bug. The correct endpoint for parent-child links is `POST /platform/tree/child-and-parents-relationships`.
- CDP-extracted `fssessionid` tokens may return 404 on write endpoints that work fine with real-browser session tokens. Test before assuming CDP tokens work for any new write endpoint.
- `GET /platform/tree/search` endpoint returns 400 errors — `q` parameter "no longer supported."

### Playwright / Chrome CDP
- `page.wait_for_timeout(N)` hangs indefinitely in CDP mode. Use `time.sleep(N/1000.0)`.
- `ctx.new_page()` can hang after Chrome restart — use `ctx.pages[0]` if a page already exists.
- Playwright MCP connection breaks when Chrome restarts. Plan Chrome restarts accordingly.
- `fetch()` from browser context inherits session cookies. `page.goto()` may drop authentication state on navigation to Ancestry/FS pages.
- For "click all matching elements": always `$$` to get all handles first, then iterate. `$` inside a loop re-finds the same element.
- Run batch scripts with `python3 -u` for real-time output. Without it, stdout buffering hides progress.

### Data Integrity
- `gps_compliance` and `confidence` stored in tree.json can be stale after bulk operations. Run GPS report and confidence recalculation after each session.
- Journal frontmatter (confidence, last_session, status) can drift from tree state. Check and resync at session start.
- Siblings should be the same generation as the direct-line sibling (Gen N), not the parents' generation (Gen N-1).
- Stored GPS/confidence fields drift from computed values after bulk operations — always recompute before committing.

### Evidence Interpretation
- Delayed birth certificates may list stepmother if biological mother died before the certificate was filed (common for certificates filed decades after birth). Cross-check against census household at birth year.
- FAG dates without source citations are Tier 5.
- FindAGrave: search married women by death-record surname, not maiden name.
- Obituaries in newspaper archives (Newspapers.com, Chronicling America) = Tier 2-3 evidence for relationships. Funeral home website obits with no newspaper attribution = Tier 4.
- Child middle names often match grandparent surnames — strong indirect evidence when paired with geographic correlation. Verify across 3+ generations.

